    <section id="volcano-experiment">
        <div class="experiment-content">
            <h2>Experiment 1: Create Your Own Erupting Volcano!</h2>
            
            <p>Have you ever wondered how a volcano erupts? Now, you can create one at home using simple materials you probably already have in your kitchen! This fun and easy experiment will not only amaze you but also teach you some cool science.</p>
            
            <h3>What Youâ€™re Making</h3>
            <p>Weâ€™re going to build a volcano and make it erupt using a fizzy reaction between baking soda and vinegar. The bubbly "lava" looks just like a real volcanic explosion (but donâ€™t worry, itâ€™s completely safe).</p>
            
            <h3>What You Need</h3>
            <ul>
            <li><strong>Baking Soda:</strong> About 2â€“3 spoonfuls.</li>
            <li><strong>Vinegar:</strong> Half a cup will do.</li>
            <li><strong>Dish Soap:</strong> Just a few drops to make extra bubbly lava.</li>
            <li><strong>Food Coloring:</strong> Red and yellow make your lava look fiery!</li>
            <li><strong>Plastic Bottle:</strong> To serve as the volcano's crater.</li>
            <li><strong>Clay or Papier-MÃ¢chÃ©:</strong> To build the volcano structure.</li>
            <li><strong>Tray:</strong> To catch the mess from the eruption.</li>
            </ul>
            
            <h3>Procedure</h3>
            <ol>
            <li>
                <strong>Build Your Volcano:</strong>
                <ul>
                <li>Use clay, papier-mÃ¢chÃ©, or play dough to shape a volcano around a plastic bottle or cup.</li>
                <li>Leave the top of the bottle open to act as the crater.</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>Get Your Volcano Ready for Action:</strong>
                <ul>
                <li>Place the volcano on a tray (trust us, it gets messy).</li>
                <li>Add 2â€“3 spoonfuls of baking soda inside the bottle.</li>
                <li>Drop a few drops of dish soap for extra foam.</li>
                <li>Add red and yellow food coloring for fiery lava.</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>Time to Erupt!</strong>
                <ul>
                <li>Pour in half a cup of vinegar and step back.</li>
                <li>Watch your volcano erupt with bubbly, colorful "lava"!</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            </ol>
            
            <h3>Whatâ€™s Happening?</h3>
            <p>Hereâ€™s the science part:</p>
            <ul>
            <li>Baking soda (a base) reacts with vinegar (an acid) to produce carbon dioxide gas.</li>
            <li>The gas bubbles push the liquid up and out, simulating a volcanic eruption.</li>
            </ul>
            
            <h3>Extra Fun Ideas</h3>
            <ul>
            <li>Experiment with different amounts of vinegar to change the eruption intensity.</li>
            <li>Research real volcanoes and compare them with your model.</li>
            <li>Try testing different "lava recipes" to see what works best.</li>
            </ul>
            
            <h3>Quick Tips</h3>
            <ul>
            <li>Perform this experiment outside or on a tray for easier cleanup.</li>
            <li>Ask an adult for help if needed.</li>
            </ul>
            
            <p><strong>Why Itâ€™s Awesome:</strong> This experiment is fun, educational, and a great way to learn about chemical reactions. Perfect for school projects or just for fun!</p>
